body:
Currently, WinML will run fine in a UWP context. However, currently, the DirectML execution provider binaries are not store compliant and will cause UWP apps to fail the Windows App Certification Kit. This will prevent the app from shipping in the store.

If the goal is to side-load the application and not upload to the windows store, then 1.5.1 or 1.4.0 can be used to create WinML+DML UWP applications.

WinML+CPU was made WACK compliant in 1.5.1 and is the recommended path currently for building apps that target the Store.

> Currently, WinML will run fine in a UWP context. However, currently, the DirectML execution provider binaries are not store compliant and will cause UWP apps to fail the Windows App Certification Kit. This will prevent the app from shipping in the store.
> 
> If the goal is to side-load the application and not upload to the windows store, then 1.5.1 or 1.4.0 can be used to create WinML+DML UWP applications.
> 
> WinML+CPU was made WACK compliant in 1.5.1 and is the recommended path currently for building apps that target the Store.

Thanks for the clarification.  Are there plans to make the DirectML execution provider binaries store compliant?
@hig-dev Thanks for the feedback. We'll look into how to appropriately do that in the next update.

@hig-dev one of the questions I have with regards to your scenario is why do you feel you need to ship your UWP app with a redistributable package of WinML while WinML (and DirectML) is already available as a standard Windows API in the operating system. Is the system version not sufficient for your use case in any way? Most UWP apps in the store using WinML simply call into the underlying Windows API.

@wchao1115 I am using a ONNX model that is converted from a PyTorch model. If I am using the current PyTorch version for the conversion and the built-in WinML, I am not able to load the converted ONNX model because of a _Failed to load model with error: Unknown model file format version._ error. I can load the same ONNX model with the WinML NuGet. In order to use the built-in WinML, I have to use an old PyTorch version (1.2.0) for the conversion and an old opset version (8).

I would prefer to ship my UWP app with the NuGet package of WinML, so that I can use a higher opset version, the current PyTorch version and support for more Windows 10 versions (see https://docs.microsoft.com/de-de/windows/ai/windows-ml/onnx-versions).

Hi @hig-dev, we looked into this issue a bit on our end and arrived at a conclusion that started with the Windows SDK 19041 (for the 20H1 update of Win10), you should be able to use and distribute DirectML through the WinML API from the WinML NuGet package with your UWP app without violating the WACK compliant. What makes this possible is the change in the SDK itself along with the related change in the WACK certification rules.
@wchao1115 I would like to try to use and test the new WinML NuGet in order to close this issue. However, my build fails. I opened a new issue under #6249.

issue.body:
**Description**
I would like to try to use the new Microsoft.AI.MachineLearning NuGet (1.6.0) but I am experiencing the following build error when I add the NuGet to my UWP project. I don't have this problem with the previous version (1.5.2).

Build configuration: Debug | x64
```
1>C:\Program Files (x86)\Microsoft Visual Studio\2019\Enterprise\MSBuild\Microsoft\VisualStudio\v16.0\AppxPackage\Microsoft.AppXPackage.Targets(6140,5): error APPX1111: Payload contains two or more files with the same destination path 'Microsoft.AI.MachineLearning.dll', but they are different sizes. Source files: 
1>C:\Program Files (x86)\Microsoft Visual Studio\2019\Enterprise\MSBuild\Microsoft\VisualStudio\v16.0\AppxPackage\Microsoft.AppXPackage.Targets(6140,5): error APPX1111: C:\Users\hig\.nuget\packages\microsoft.ai.machinelearning\1.6.0\build\uap\..\..\runtimes\win-x64\uap\Microsoft.AI.MachineLearning.dll
1>C:\Program Files (x86)\Microsoft Visual Studio\2019\Enterprise\MSBuild\Microsoft\VisualStudio\v16.0\AppxPackage\Microsoft.AppXPackage.Targets(6140,5): error APPX1111: C:\Users\hig\.nuget\packages\microsoft.ai.machinelearning\1.6.0\runtimes\win-x64\native\static\microsoft.ai.machinelearning.dll 
```

The target of my app is Build 19041 and the min version is Build 18362 and I am using the latest Visual Studio 16.8.3. 

**Urgency**
I would like to test the new version in order to close #5389.

**System information**
- OS Platform and Distribution: Windows 10 x64 (20H2) (Build 19042)
- ONNX Runtime installed from (source or binary): NuGet
- ONNX Runtime version: 1.6.0
- Visual Studio version: 16.8.3

**To Reproduce**
- Create a UWP project that targets Build 19041
- Add Microsoft.AI.MachineLearning NuGet (1.6.0)
- Build for Debug | x64

**Expected behavior**
The build runs without errors.

body: I checked the new 1.8.0 release and it works now. Thanks.
